TITLE: Republican Votes Helped Washington Pile Up Debt
SUMMARY: As they escalate a debt-limit standoff, House Republicans blame President Biden’s spending bills for an increase in deficits. Voting records show otherwise.

TITLE: You’re Now a ‘Manager.’ Forget About Overtime Pay.
SUMMARY: New evidence shows that many employers are mislabeling rank-and-file workers as managers to avoid paying them overtime.

TITLE: Why Companies Are Pushing Premium Products With Higher Prices
SUMMARY: Companies are trying to maintain fat profits as the economy changes, making “premiumization” their new favorite buzzword.

TITLE: Biden’s World Bank Pick Looks to Link Climate and Development Goals
SUMMARY: Ajay Banga will begin a monthlong “global listening tour” to drum up support for his nomination to be the bank’s next president.

TITLE: Rules to Curb Illicit Dollar Flows Create Unintended Hardships for Some Iraqis
SUMMARY: The regulations were meant to prevent dollar transfers to corrupt actors. But they have ended up harming ordinary Iraqis who need U.S. currency for legitimate purposes.

TITLE: Eurozone Inflation Edges Lower, but Pressure on Prices Continues
SUMMARY: The annual rate of inflation was 8.5 percent in February, down from 8.6 percent a month earlier, among countries using the euro.

TITLE: Starbucks Violated Labor Law in Buffalo Union Drive, Judge Rules
SUMMARY: The decision cited “egregious and widespread misconduct,” including illegal monitoring and firing of workers. Starbucks signaled that it would appeal.

TITLE: Low-Income Families Brace for End of Extra Food Stamp Benefits
SUMMARY: When a pandemic-era boost ends on Wednesday, more than 30 million people will lose a significant amount of assistance.

TITLE: Biden’s Semiconductor Plan Bets on Federal Aid to Change Corporate Behavior
SUMMARY: The administration says the conditions it has attached to $40 billion in new subsidies will help U.S. semiconductor makers compete globally. Some economists disagree.

TITLE: Biden Nominates Julie Su as US Labor Secretary
SUMMARY: President Biden’s choice to lead the Labor Department is the deputy to the incumbent, Martin J. Walsh, who is leaving the administration.

TITLE: What’s in the CHIPS Act, Aimed at Childcare Expansion and National Security
SUMMARY: A sprawling new program for the semiconductor industry is foremost about national security, but it will try to advance other priorities as well.

TITLE: For Ukraine’s Animals, a Home Is Getting Harder to Find
SUMMARY: Early in the war, thousands of pets were ferried out of danger, mostly to other European countries. But now adoptions are waning.

TITLE: Biden’s Semiconductor Plan Flexes the Power of the Federal Government
SUMMARY: In return for vast subsidies, the Biden administration is asking the chip industry to make promises about its workers and finances.

TITLE: To Tap Federal Funds, Chip Makers Will Need to Provide Child Care
SUMMARY: The move seeks to help more women join the work force as industry leaders complain of labor shortages.

TITLE: IRS Decision Not to Tax Certain Payments Carries Fiscal Cost
SUMMARY: The Biden administration has opted not to tax state payments to residents, a decision that could add to the nation’s fiscal woes.

TITLE: What Layoffs? Many Employers Are Eager to Hang On to Workers.
SUMMARY: Despite interest rate increases meant to cool the labor market, companies outside the tech industry worry about having too few workers, not too many.

TITLE: War in Ukraine Deepens Divide Among Major Economies at G20 Gathering
SUMMARY: Treasury Secretary Janet L. Yellen urged her counterparts at a summit in India to condemn Russia’s actions, and she defended the cost of supplying aid to Kyiv.

TITLE: The Furniture Hustlers of Silicon Valley
SUMMARY: As tech companies cut costs and move to remote work, their left-behind office furniture has become part of a booming trade.

TITLE: How the Fed Opened Pandora’s Box
SUMMARY: Jerome H. Powell’s no-holds-barred response to the pandemic was made possible by history. It raises questions about the future.

TITLE: The Fed’s Preferred Inflation Gauge Sped Back Up
SUMMARY: Inflation is down from its peak last summer, but recent readings have shown substantial and surprising staying power.
